# PART 3: DEEP COMPETITOR ANALYSIS\par
\par
## 3.1 Hipcamp (USA/Australia/Canada) \emdash  The Blueprint\par
\par
**What it is:**\par
Hipcamp's platform allows landowners (referred to as 'hosts') to list their land for camping, glamping, RV stays, and more, while outdoor enthusiasts (referred to as 'campers') can discover and book these unique outdoor stays.\par
\par
**Business Model:**\par
Hipcamp operates under a sharing economy business model, similar to platforms like Airbnb. The company shifted to a split-fee model, placing a ~10% booking fee on campers and 10% on hosts.\par
\par
It's free to list on Hipcamp, with no contract or monthly fees. This is critical \emdash  the zero barrier to host entry drives supply growth aggressively.\par
\par
**Host Earnings:**\par
Rural property with a basic campsite: $3,000\endash $10,000/year. Scenic location with multiple campsites: $10,000\endash $50,000/year. Established property with a range of sites and amenities: $50,000\endash $100,000+/year.\par
\par
**What makes Hipcamp great:**\par
Campers can search the platform based on location, amenities, and price to find the perfect outdoor accommodation. This model fosters a sense of community and sustainability, as it enables private landowners to generate income while preserving and sharing their land with others.\par
\par
Hipcamp recently added a feature that allows hosts to offer additional perks, whether it's a picnic dinner, group horseback ride, yoga session or an ecology tour. \emdash  This is the future direction for CampIn as well: experiences layered on top of stays.\par
\par
**Hipcamp's Growth Story:**\par
Hipcamp's website launched in June 2013, and only a couple of people used the website daily over the course of its first summer. However, it took off over the course of the next year, primarily growing user traffic through SEO, word-of-mouth, and guerrilla marketing efforts.\par
\par
**KEY LESSON FOR CAMPIN:** Hipcamp was hyper-patient in the beginning. They grew through SEO, word-of-mouth, and a genuine community \emdash  not paid ads. CampIn must take the same approach. Build it slowly. Build it right.\par
\par
---\par
\par
## 3.2 CampMonk (India) \emdash  The Closest Local Competitor\par
\par
**What it is:**\par
CampMonk is a platform to discover & book camping holidays (consisting of activities and campsite accommodation).\par
\par
Camp Monk empowers landowners to host campers and provide them with local food, culture, and nature experiences. Camp Monk focuses on preservation of land and a zero impact model.\par
\par
**Business size & limitations:**\par
CampMonk is a seed company based in Bengaluru, India, founded in 2016. It has raised $383K in funding. Camp Monk's revenue is approximately < $1M.\par
\par
After **9 years**, CampMonk is still under $1M revenue. This tells us something critical: **existing Indian camping platforms have failed to scale** because they tried to be curators and operators, not true marketplace platforms.\par
\par
While it is easy finding good and safe camping grounds in many developed travel markets, in India the story is very different. Camping is still an emerging concept in India and few landowners are open to the idea of opening up their properties to campers.\par
\par
**KEY LESSON FOR CAMPIN:**\par
CampMonk stayed small and South India focused. It operates primarily as a curated listing service, not a true two-sided marketplace. CampIn can win by:\par
1. Being truly national from day one\par
2. Building a genuine community, not just listings\par
3. Adding the campervan/road-travel angle CampMonk ignores\par
4. Feeling emotionally premium and human, not transactional\par
\par
---\par
\par
## 3.3 HireACamp (India) \emdash  The Booking-First Approach\par
\par
**What it is:**\par
HireACamp is like AirBnB for camping and India's first platform through which travellers can book their stay instantly anywhere in the country.\par
\par
**Revenue Model:**\par
HireACamp works on a simple revenue model where a certain commission is charged (from the host) on each booking made through the platform.\par
\par
The Dehradun-based startup provides a single platform for travellers to search, discover, and instantly book from a wide range of campsites offered on the marketplace, including hill, beach, jungle, luxury, and budget camping.\par
\par
**Where HireACamp falls short:**\par
HireACamp is purely booking-focused. It has no community angle, no road-travel infrastructure support, no emotional storytelling, and no campervan culture integration. Its UX feels like a standard travel booking portal. It received seed funding from Indian Angel Network but has not scaled to dominance. The platform also has very limited mobile experience.\par
\par
**KEY LESSON FOR CAMPIN:** HireACamp proved the model works in India (commission on bookings from hosts). But they failed to build the culture layer. CampIn wins the culture layer.\par
\par
---\par
\par
## 3.4 OverlandingCamping.com (India) \emdash  The Community-First Content Play\par
\par
This platform is oriented around the overlanding culture \emdash  SUVs, off-road trips, and self-sufficient travel. It is community and content-driven more than booking-driven.\par
\par
**KEY LESSON FOR CAMPIN:** The overlanding/road-travel community in India is passionate, engaged, and deeply underserved by booking platforms. CampIn can absorb this community by being the **place they finally trust for overnight stops** \emdash  something no one has built yet.\par
